00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:41.000
to allow you to share it either via GitHub, through, you know, your GitHub's firewall,

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.960
or, you know, you can have it saved in a local directory.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:46.960
So, yeah.

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:51.600
So, you know, why package your function in a library?

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:57.639
If you've ever had this internal thought process, you know, where did I save that function again?

00:02:57.639 --> 00:03:01.960
Like, you're building something, you create this cool function, and you're like, hey,

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:05.000
I want to use that function again, but where did I save it?

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Where did I put it?

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:07.000
What file?

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:08.000
Like, what folder?

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Did I delete it?

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Oh, my gosh.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:11.000
That's, like, that's scary.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:12.639
You know, you know, why can't I find this function?

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:15.520
You know, you start spiraling, you know, what did I do?

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:18.000
Did I save it in a notepad, an R markdown?

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.320
Did I print it out and then fax it to myself?

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:22.520
Like, you're going south, you know?

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:27.360
You know, I'll just rewrite the function.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:30.399
You know, it takes you 30 minutes, an hour, two hours, again, to rewrite it.

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:34.600
And so this is the idea of, like, packaging your code, is that you want to take those

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:38.039
functions, package them up so that they're already in your R environment, and then you

00:03:38.039 --> 00:03:40.039
could just load them up and then use them.

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:43.720
And then also to allow your co-workers to use them and inspire them, and maybe they're

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:47.160
having the same problems, or maybe they didn't realize that they could create a function

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:49.720
like that because they're just so busy.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:57.320
So yeah, so I'm just going to skip through this part.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:00.520
So let's just cover what a function is real fast.

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:08.279
So a function is a set of statements that, when combined, performs a specific task.

00:04:08.279 --> 00:04:12.720
So an example that we're going to use, we're going to use this function for when we build

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:13.919
our package.

00:04:13.919 --> 00:04:15.880
So we're going to build a not-in function.

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:19.239
So for anybody who used SQL, there's an in and a not-in.

00:04:19.239 --> 00:04:23.000
And the in function, you know, filters on a list of values.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.519
Not-in does the opposite.

00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:29.679
And that's nice, because let's say you have, like, a list of 20 things, and you want to

00:04:29.679 --> 00:04:31.200
exclude only two of them.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:36.320
You don't want to list out 18, you only want to list the two, so you can include the 18.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:39.440
So in order to create that function, all we're going to do, and it's really simple,

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:45.160
is we're going to go negate, in, and now we have our not-in function right there.

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:50.399
So we're going to use this to create our library.

00:04:50.399 --> 00:04:54.480
So what we're going to do is we're on a clean R document.

00:04:54.480 --> 00:05:00.440
We're going to go file, new, package, new directory, and then R package right here.

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:07.679
And we're going to call this Danalytics, because my name's Dan, and it's my talk.

00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:09.880
Create package.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:12.200
And then once we create a package, you can already see there's already some default things.

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:15.359
They have a print hello world, which is just called hello.

